This project focuses on the design and performance analysis of compact and highly efficient address decoders for SRAM arrays, targeting improvements in speed, power consumption, and area optimization.

In modern VLSI systems, SRAM plays a critical role in cache memories and high-speed applications. The address decoder significantly impacts overall memory performance, as it contributes a large portion of access delay and power consumption.

This work explores advanced decoder architectures such as:

Pre-decoded hierarchical structures
NAND-NOR based compact decoder designs
Optimized transistor-level implementations

The proposed designs are analyzed and compared with conventional decoders in terms of:

⏱️ Propagation delay
⚡ Power consumption
📐 Area efficiency (transistor count)
⚙️ Performance (PPA metrics)

Simulation and analysis are carried out using industry-standard tools like Cadence Virtuoso, considering CMOS/FinFET technologies.

🎯 Objectives
Design compact SRAM row/column decoders
Reduce access time and power dissipation
Optimize transistor count and layout area
Perform comparative analysis with conventional architectures

