🧠 Technical Background
In SRAM architecture, the decoder converts an n-bit address into 2ⁿ word lines, enabling access to a specific memory cell. The decoder design directly affects memory access time and power consumption.
To improve efficiency, modern designs use:
Predecoding techniques to reduce logic complexity
Hierarchical decoding for large memory arrays
Replica circuits for timing accuracy
Compact logic styles to minimize transistor usage

